{
  "metadata": {
    "anchor_id": "member_d",
    "description": "31-year-old female, PPO plan. First pregnancy — full maternity journey with surprise billing dispute. Prenatal care Jan–Sep, L&D Oct, surprise out-of-network anesthesia bill → appeal → No Surprises Act resolution. Jan–Nov 2025.",
    "created": "2026-03-06",
    "narrative_summary": "Sarah Chen is a 31-year-old first-time mother in Portland, OR on a PPO plan with her spouse David. Her story covers the full maternity journey from initial OB confirmation through delivery. Prenatal care was routine — regular visits, screenings, ultrasounds, glucose tolerance test (normal), Tdap vaccine. At 32 weeks, baby was measuring large so an additional growth scan was authorized. She delivered vaginally in October at University Hospital with a 2-night stay. Two weeks later she received a $4,200 balance bill from the anesthesiologist (epidural) who was out-of-network — the hospital assigned them, Sarah had no choice. The claim was denied for out-of-network provider. Sarah called member services, very upset. An appeal was filed citing the No Surprises Act. The appeal was approved, the claim was reprocessed as in-network, and Sarah's out-of-pocket responsibility was reduced to her normal coinsurance amount."
  },

